<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,356,1211]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,396,536,563]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">Taxonomic note.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hacker, H. H. &amp; Schreier, H. P. &amp; Goater, B." box="[402,628,536,563]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" pagination="7 - 612" refId="ref11451" refString="Hacker, H. H., Schreier, H. P. &amp; Goater, B. (2012) Revision of the tribe Nolini of Africa and the Western Palaearctic Region (Lepidoptera, Noctuoidea, Noctuidae, Nolinae). Esperiana, 17, 7 - 612." type="journal article" year="2012">
Hacker 
<emphasis box="[490,546,536,562]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
illustrated male and female 
<typeStatus box="[945,1043,537,563]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hampson, 1901" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1901" box="[1080,1431,536,563]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transecta">
<emphasis box="[1080,1245,536,562]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">Nola transecta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson, G. F." box="[1252,1431,537,563]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" pagination="165 - 186" refId="ref11502" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1901) New species of Syntomidae and Arctiadae. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 7, 8 (45), 165 - 186. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03745480109442907" type="journal article" year="1901">Hampson, 1901</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, following the original generic combination without attempting to revise the generic assignment of the species. The author of this paper had the opportunity to dissect a male 
<typeStatus box="[805,892,609,635]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">syntype</typeStatus>
in order to obtain morphological information to clarify the taxonomy of this peculiar species. The configuration of the male genitalia has revealed a close affinity to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laszlo, Ronkay &amp; Ronkay" authorityYear="2015" box="[151,294,680,706]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Hampsonola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,294,680,706]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">Hampsonola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
characterized by the bilobate valva comprised of a narrow, long dorsal lobe and a short ventral lobe and the conspicuously elongate harpe. This species, however, does not have androconial scales on the valva, additionally possessing a fully developed uncus, reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName box="[723,837,752,778]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[723,837,752,778]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">Meganola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and an extensive ventro-distal sclerotized plate of the valva. It is difficult to establish whether these characters represent generic autapomorphies without conducting in depth genetic studies, therefore the species is tentatively placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laszlo, Ronkay &amp; Ronkay" authorityYear="2015" box="[1022,1165,824,850]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Hampsonola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1022,1165,824,850]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">Hampsonola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hampson, 1901)" authorityName="László" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Hampsonola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transecta" status="comb. n.">
<emphasis box="[1181,1436,824,850]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">Hampsonola transecta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson, G. F." box="[159,339,861,887]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" pagination="165 - 186" refId="ref11502" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1901) New species of Syntomidae and Arctiadae. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 7, 8 (45), 165 - 186. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03745480109442907" type="journal article" year="1901">Hampson, 1901</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[354,456,861,887]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[354,456,861,887]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153" rank="species">comb. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="153" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,356,1211]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,723,896,923]" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">
Description of the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[621,710,896,922]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–27" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1448,1472]" captionTargetBox="[155,1417,189,1417]" captionTargetId="figure-22@8.[152,1435,181,1424]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22–27. male genitalia, a: clasping apparatus, b: aedeagus (coll. ANHRT, unless otherwise indicated). 22, Hampsonola elachistomorpha, Zambia, LGNA 1062; 23, H. aulombardiella, Kenya, LGNA 1298 (coll. A. Kingston); 24, H. argyropasta, Liberia, LGNA 1229; 25, H. nanographa, Gabon, LGNA 1227; 26, H. transecta, syntype of Nola transecta, Sierra Leone, NHMUK 010317594 (prepared by László) (©NHMUK); 27, Gabonola gen. n. smithi sp. n., holotype, Gabon, LGNA 1171." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920080" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920080/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="153">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Uncus rather long, narrow, medially slightly dilated, distally tapered, apically pointed. Tegumen elongate, very narrow; subscaphium short, narrow, weakly sclerotized. Valva narrow basally, dorsal lobe long, slightly curved, distally gradually dilated with apex rounded, costal margin rather wide at base, then abruptly narrowed and gradually dilated towards apex. Ventral lobe of valva moderately long, more or less quadrangular, distal margin depressed, ventro-distally bearing a conspicuous, heavily sclerotized, broad L-shaped plate. Sacculus short and narrow, weakly sclerotized; harpe relatively small, bulb-shaped basally continued in a very thin, gently curved needle-like distal process. Juxta small, shield-like; vinculum moderately long, pointed V-shaped. Aedeagus short, dilated medially, gradually tapered to pointed apex, coecum moderately long, narrow, rounded; vesica without cornuti or scobination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
